  "summary": "A man discusses his wife, Edie, a former member of the Women's Auxiliary Air Force, noting that her father's assets were left to Alexander. While Lucy prepares lunch in the kitchen, Alexander and West arrive, and Alexander mentions that a Scotland Yard officer is visiting. He notes that Uncle Harold is angry about the ongoing murder investigation. Mr. Wimbush informs Emma that Inspector Claddock from Scotland Yard is now leading the case. Wimbush suggests the victim was likely a foreigner from London, prompting Emma to suggest the woman might be French, a thought that visibly unsettles her.\n\nDuring lunch, the family members react differently to the murder: Cedric treats the event as a morbid joke, Harold is offended, Emma is worried, and Alfred remains lost in thought. Following the meal, Inspector Claddock and Inspector Bacon question Cedric. Cedric explains that he returned from the Balearic Islands on December 21st after receiving an electric telegram from Emma, and that he left again on the 27th. He denies having any knowledge of a connection between the victim and the estate. After the questioning, Inspector Bacon expresses his personal dislike for Cedric, labeling him a self-righteous, \"artistic type\" and a \"loose cannon.\" Bacon criticizes Cedric's disrespectful clothing and suggests that he is the type of person capable of strangling a woman without remorse.",
